Course.WEBDESCRIPTION:
This course focuses on the essential knowledge and skills required to successfully work in a vocational educational learning environment. You will learn how to manage your OH&S responsibilities, discover how the VET sector operates, be able to unpack training packages to meet client needs and ensure your learning and assessment demonstrates inclusive practice.
Please Note: In order to successfully complete this qualification you will need to deliver training for a group of learners in your workplace. If you are not currently employed as a trainer we will ask you to either volunteer your services to a community organisation OR we will provide a simulated workplace on your behalf.
h2. Agenda
During this course the intention is that the following topics will be covered, but not necessarily in the order given. Due to the variable nature of Adult Education classes, parts of the curriculum may be adapted to suit the needs of the class.
Content:
* The VET Sector – an overview * Expectation of Trainer and Assessors in the VET sector * Meet clients’ needs with training packages * OH&S responsibilities and legislation * Your role in ensuring a safe and healthy learning environment * Identify hazards in the learning environment * Assess risks * Develop action plans and monitoring the learning environment * What is inclusivity? * Relevant legislation to support inclusivity * Resources to support inclusivity * Your role in practicing and promoting inclusivity * Work practices to support an inclusive culture
h2. Objectives
The intended Learning Outcomes for this course are as follows.
By the end of this course, students will be able to:
* Explain the components of Vocational Education & Training Sector (VET) * Discuss and identify relevant workplace standards or benchmarks * Identify and unpack the different parts of a training package in particular a unit of competency * Define and discuss the concept of inclusivity in a learning/assessment environment * Select appropriate solutions, which could assist with different inclusivity issues in a learning context * Identify the OH&S responsibilities of trainers and assessors * Complete an OH&S hazard/ risk assessment in a simulated environment
Any student attending an accredited course must present photo ID at their first class to receive their qualification.
PLS NOTE: All classes need a minimum number of students to go ahead. If your course does not have enough students it will be cancelled and you will be informed. ***Please be aware that you maybe be informed of a cancellation &/or change via SMS or E-mail.

Node.NAME: St. Trinians College
Node.CONTENTS:
St. Trinians College has been serving the inner city area for over thirty years and is a non-profit incorporated organisation, partly funded by the NSW Board of Adult and Community Education (BACE).
We offer a wide range of day and evening courses. You must be 15 years old to join a class, but there is no upper limit.
We accept people from any suburb. The College has a voluntary Management Committee who are listed below.
h3. Mission Statement
To provide the people in the inner city region with equitable opportunities to access quality adult vocational and personal enrichment education.
h3. Quality Policy
St. Trinians College is an established Adult Education provider committed to giving customers quality training and service which meets or exceeds their expectations. The College adheres to the Standards of the Australian Quality Framework. Our objective is to maintain a quality system which will enable us to continuously monitor and improve our proceedures, programs and services. Commitment to quality is the responsibility of every member of the organisation.
